email_text: Subject: distributions         Hi Steve,         Thanks for your help on this. Here is what Mel and I are looking at for 2022:         May 2022 - received check for $34,535. Memo indicates it is for Q1 distribution and 2022 true up. By my calculations from what the Board voted to distribute and my ownership, roughly $13,500 should be Q1 distribution and $21,000 true up         August 2022 - received check for $17,504. Memo indicates it is for Q2 distribution and 2021 equalization. By my calculations almost all of this should be distribution.         So our total distribution from those two checks is roughly $31K. Adding the roughly $70K that is coming now that brings our total for 2022 to $101k in distributions. But the K1 says we had $138K in distributions on allocated earnings of $265K in earnings. This also doesn't make sense to me since we were supposed to be distributing 42.5% which for me should have been around  $112,625.         Thanks again, and I hope you had a nice Easter weekend.    Megan

Subject: Hayden Coursey        Hello Mrs Smith,     Hayden was officially diagnosed with ADD yesterday and he started Concerta today. He has been struggling mightily and very burned out, but glad we figured out why. Apparently his therapist had suspicions years ago but she thinks the lack of academic rigor during the pandemic and then at his middle schools masked his issues. He was diagnosed by his psychiatrist but we are proceeding with full psychoeducational testing to be sure we arenâ€™t missing anything else. I will keep you upd.     Regarding midterms - I saw the schedule and I assume that kids with extended time go to a different location than kids without. Could you tell me where Hayden is supposed to go for his exams?     Thanks,  Megan Coursey     Sent from my iPhone

subject:	UHP Upper-Level Event: Williamsburg, VA - Colonial and Water Country USA    Hi Wolfpack,    I'm pleased to introduce the second Upper-Level Event of the summer -- the University Honors Program is heading back up to Virginia for a weekend in Williamsburg!    Screenshot 2024-05-19 at 1.27.52 PM.png    We'll have a Friday morning departure on June 7th and spend the afternoon exploring Colonial Williamsburg; we'll tour the Governor's Palace, Capitol, and Raleigh Tavern, and we'll visit trade shops, historic houses, and exhibition sites of Williamsburg's 18th century residents. Then we'll check into The Historic Powhatan, a residences resort with amenities including: indoor and outdoor pools, a sauna, tennis and racquetball courts, and a mini-golf course.    Saturday will be devoted to Water Country USA, Virginia's largest water park -- wave pools, lazy rivers, water coasters, live entertainment, and more! We'll call it quits when the park closes at 7pm and return to The Historic Powhatan for one more night before our departure on Sunday morning.     Including transportation, two nights at The Historic Powhatan, a half day at Colonial Williamsburg, and a full day at Water Country USA, this trip is available to UHP students at the low cost of $95. If this trip sounds like something you absolutely must add to your summer, please fill out this google form.    Thank you and have a great week!    --  Morgan Budzynski (she/her)  North Carolina State University  M.A. in Rhetoric and Composition C/O 2025  Administrative Assistant, University Honors Program

sent by:	melobsin@ncsu.edu  reply-to:	melobsin@ncsu.edu  to:	  bcc:	group-scholars-students-all@ncsu.edu  :	Apr 29, 2024, 1:23â€¯PM  subject:	UHP Requirements Explained: High Impact Experiences    UHP Requirements Explained: High Impact Experiences  University Honors students (admitted for the Fall of 2022 or later) and University Scholars students complete a total of three high impact experiences (HIEs) by the time they graduate. These are opportunities for students to engage in experiential learning outside the classroom in a way that directly aligns with their individual goals. This requirement also gives students the opportunity to reflect on how these experiences impact their learning in preparation for life after college such as graduate school or employment applications.    This email is meant to serve as a gentle reminder that if you completed what would qualify as a High Impact Experience at any point during this academic school year, it is preferred you submit your reflection essay for that HIE before we get very far into the summer months. DO NOT stress over writing these reflections before your final exams are over, but please do submit them sometime soon after! Ideally, going forward, we would like students to submit their reflections within the same semester that their HIE concluded (within 4-6 weeks) so that the experience is still fresh in their minds and they have plenty of details to share in their reflection essay.    DISCIPLINARY BREADTH EXCEPTION: the exception to the above â€œdeadline guidelineâ€ of â€œwithin 4-6 weeks of the experience concludingâ€ is our â€œDisciplinary Breadthâ€ category. If a student is double majoring or majoring and minoring in academic programs from two different academic colleges, we would rather you wait until the semester of your graduation to reflect on what studying under those differing academic programs has done for you as a person and future professional.     An explanation of the High Impact Experience requirement has always been linked on our website, but we have also recently recorded a short (4:19) video, linked below with a transcript, to better explain the HIE requirement and the various HIE categories under which students can submit their HIE reflections.    Since this video was recorded, an additional slide has been added to the HIEs Explained slide deck with some examples of professional and/or personally developmental opportunities available to students from around the University that would definitely qualify as a High Impact Experience upon successful completion.    HONORS CAPSTONE PROJECT : Remember that students who submit their undergraduate research as an Honors Capstone Project can earn two out of their three required High Impact Experiences at once!    If you have any questions or concerns about the High Impact Experience requirement for the Honors Program, please reach out to your Honors Program advisor.    To submit a High Impact Experience reflection essay, please use this Google Form.        Watch the Video (4:19) + Read the Transcript arrow        Facebook  Facebook  Instagram  Instagram         --  University Honors Program  NC State University  University College, Division of Academic and Student Affairs (DASA)  221 Jensen Drive, #219 Clark Hall  Campus Box 8610  Raleigh, NC 27695  P: 919-515-2353  F: 919-513-4392  honors.dasa.ncsu.edu      Advisor	       Advisees  Anne Auten	Last names beginning with A-Cn  Sean Cassidy	Last names beginning with Co-Gra  Ken Johnson	Last names beginning with Grb-Lar  Sean Cassidy	Last names beginning with Las-Pan  Meghan Teten	Last names beginning with Pao-Sie  Emily Koester	Last names beginning with Sif-Z    "All electronic mail messages in connection with State business that are sent to or received by this account are subject to the NC Public Records Law. subject:	IMPORTANT ECE 403 001 Exam Tomorrow    Good Afternoon,    You do not know me because I am not in one of your classes but Iâ€™m reaching out to you on behalf of one of your current students Owen Gabriel Gromyko.    Iâ€™m honestly not sure if he is in your class but i know he is in ECE 401 001 and is expecting to take an exam tomorrow at 8:30. If he is not one of your students, I apologize and hope you can redirect me accordingly.    Iâ€™m sure this is unusual, but I want to ask if it would even be possible for him to take his exam at least later in the day. He is sick with what I believe is the flu. Iâ€™ve been tending to him for a bit and he is having HORRIBLE muscle fatigue, sweats, pains, etc. All classic signs of the flu. I came over after he took an exam this morning and he told me how bad he was doing and that he had no pain meds for his headache. As his partner I came to help him. Iâ€™ve been on his bedside changing a cool cloth every few minutes because his temperature keeps causing it to heat up so quickly. Unfortunately he doesnâ€™t have a thermometer where he lives so I canâ€™t even send formal proof of his state.     I told him to try and reach out earlier but he assured me there was no way his exam could be considered for a later time. However, considering the increased emphasis on student health physically and mentally, I was hoping you would consider, if nothing else, allowing him to take the exam at a different hour. As Iâ€™m sure you can conclude, being this sick and worrying about an 8:30 am exam is not ideal for the healing process.    I do apologize for any inconvenience this may cause or disrespect this may come across as on my part, but I want what is best for him and Iâ€™m confident an exam tomorrow is not that, much less at 8:30 in the morning.    I did not copy him on this email because I did not want his hopes to get up; plus I know him and heâ€™d probably try to tough it out instead of risking offending a professor. I hope you will consider what I am suggesting.    Best,  Chloe Coursey

The Department of History has some fantastic internship opportunities available, and the department welcomes applications from all majors. Sincerely,  Office of the Department of History  Carnegie Mellon University.

Subject: BME385 : Inquiry Regarding Results Section and RMSE Calculation  To: Derek Kramper <dgkamper@ncsu.edu>  Hi Dr. Kamper,     I hope you had a great weekend. I apologize for reaching out with last-minute queries. Currently, my lab partner and I are working on the Results section, and I am a bit confused with the data representation. If I recall correctly, you mentioned that we need a data table for Voltage vs. Force. Could you please confirm if we can report the average of the voltage output for each force? Attached is a screenshot of the table I made, using the averaged voltages.I'm also not sure how to find the RMSE values because I don't know how to calculate the expected force values. Do you mind giving me a hint for this?     Thank you for your time and guidance!    Best,  CN

Subject: RE:BME385 : Inquiry Regarding Results Section and RMSE Calculation  To:   Hi Cyndy,    You should include all of the data in your table (3 separate measurements for each force). RMSE refers to the fit of the model -   what is the difference between your data points and the value predicted by the line or the quadratic curve predicted by the model  (RMSE for the fit of each model).      Best,  Derek Kamper, Ph.D.  Associate Professor, Joint Department of Biomedical Engineering  Associate Director, Closed Loop Engineering for Advanced Rehabilitation (CLEAR)  North Carolina State University  University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill  (919) 515-4411

Subject: BME 375 Final Exam - Cindy Nguyen  Hi Bob,    Please see below for my answers to the final exam questions. I want to take this opportunity to thank you for your guidance and support throughout the course. Your insights have been invaluable to my learning experience. Thank you once again.    *************************************    Microcontrollers I - Spring 2024    FINAL EXAMINATION      Q1: Describe in 1 or 2 sentences what each of these Arduino functions or operators do:        random(min, max): Generates pseudo-random numbers. It returns a random number between min and max-1.            delay(): Pauses the program for the amount of time (in milliseconds) specified as a parameter. It is useful for creating   longer delays where timing precision is not critical.            delayMicroseconds(): This function pauses the program for the specified number of microseconds. It is useful for creating   very short delays, especially when working with timing-sensitive components (i.e. sensors or communication protocols).            micros(): Returns the number of microseconds since the Arduino board began running the current program.            millis():  Returns the number of milliseconds since the Arduino board began running the current program            analogWrite(): generates a PWM signal on a specified pin, allowing control over the output voltage level, which is   useful for controlling the brightness of an LED, the speed of a motor, or the position of a servo.            !=  (example: x != y): stands for "not equal to" and is used to compare two values. The expression x != y evaluates   to â€˜trueâ€™ if x is not equal to y, and â€˜falseâ€™ otherwise.            %:  Calculates the remainder when one integer is divided by another.            &&: It is the logical AND operator used to combine two conditions. It returns true if both conditions it connects   are true, and false            ==: Compares the left variable with the right value or variable in the operator, returning â€˜trueâ€™ if they are equal.            =:   It is the assignment operator used to assign a value to a variable            EEPROM.put():  Writes values to the EEPROM using variable semantics.            EEPROM.get():  Retrieves values from EEPROM so that we can print them as floats on the serial monitor using Serial.print()  or Serial.println()         Q2: For the millis() function, how long will the counter run before it overflows (reaches its maximum then starts counting again from zero)?        The counter is an â€˜unsigned longâ€™ type, which means it can hold values from  0 to 4,294,967,295 (2^32 - 1). This number will overflow (go back to zero), after approximately  50 days.        Q3: For the micros() function, how long will the counter run before it overflows (reaches its maximum then starts counting again from zero)?        The counter is an â€˜unsigned longâ€™ type, which means it can hold values from 0 to 4,294,967,295 (2^32 - 1). This number will overflow (go back to zero), after approximately  71.6 minutes.        Q4: For the analogWrite() function, using your Arduino Uno, what are the PWM frequencies that you would get on the analog output pins?        The Arduino Uno's analogWrite() function uses PWM on pins 3, 5, 6, 9, 10, and 11. The PWM frequency on most pins is around  490 Hz, while pins 5 and 6 have a frequency of around  980 Hz.         Q5: On the Arduino Uno, several data types are available.  For the data type "int":     - How many bytes are stored in an "int"?        There are 2 bytes in an â€œintâ€.       - What are the minimum and maximum values that can be stored in an int?        The minimum value that can be stored is -32,768,   and the maximum value is 32,767 in an int.        Q6: On the Arduino Uno, several data types are available.  For the data type "float":     - How many bytes are stored in a "float"?         There are 4 bytes in a â€œfloatâ€.       - What are the minimum and maximum values that can be stored in a float?        â€œfloatâ€ data type can represent a wide range of values. The minimum value that can be stored in a float is -3.4028235E+38 and   the maximum value is 3.4028235E+38.        Q7: On the Arduino Uno, several data types are available.  For the data type "unsigned int":     - How many bytes are stored in an "unsigned int"?        There are 2 bytes in an â€œunsigned intâ€.       - What are the minimum and maximum values that can be stored in an unsigned int?        The minimum value that can be stored in an unsigned int is  0, and the maximum value is  65,535.        Q8: On the Arduino Uno, several data types are available.  For the data type "long":     - How many bytes are stored in a "long"?        There are 4 bytes in â€œlongâ€.       - What are the minimum and maximum values that can be stored in a long?        The minimum value that can be stored in a long is  -2,147,483,648, and the maximum value is  2,147,483,647.        Q9: Many Arduino circuits are built using a solderless breadboard. These can cause problems. Describe at least one major problem that can be caused by using a solderless breadboard?        Solderless breadboards can cause problems with complex circuits because of the large amount of wiring required. A major issue with solderless breadboards is their less secure connections compared to   soldered ones, which can lead to unreliable circuit behavior especially with high-frequency or high-current circuits.        Q10:    What is an "internal pullup"?        An "internal pullup" is a resistor that can be internally connected to a digital input pin in an Arduino. It pulls the pin's voltage to HIGH (5V) when the pin is not actively driven LOW (0V), helping   maintain a defined voltage level on the pin in the absence of an external circuit. This prevents floating inputs and reduces electrical noise.        How do you use it (how do you activate it)?        To activate the internal pullup resistor, you use the  pinMode()  function with the mode INPUT_PULLUP. For example,  pinMode(pin, INPUT_PULLUP);        What command is used by Arduino to activate an internal pullup?        pinMode(pin, INPUT_PULLUP);        What does it do?        The INPUT_PULLUP mode in Arduino sets a digital pin to the HIGH level by connecting an internal resistor between the digital pin and the power supply (VCC). This pull-up resistor typically has a value   of around 20-50 kÎ© and helps prevent floating inputs, which can lead to high current consumption.        Why would you use it?        An internal pullup is used to simplify circuit design by removing the necessity for an external resistor to pull a digital input pin to the HIGH level. This is particularly useful when connecting switches   or buttons that are normally open, as the internal pullup resistor ensures a stable HIGH state when the switch or button is not pressed.        Q11: To find answers to questions you may have in the future, for further learning, or to see new project Ideas, list at least three resources that are freely available to you:        Arduino Forum: The forum is helpful for seeking answers to Arduino-related questions and discovering fresh project   ideas.          ChatGPT:  It's a useful tool for debugging code and getting answers to various questions, although its accuracy may vary.          Classmates:  Other students in the class could offer insights and solutions to common problems, making them a great resource for addressing questions.          Youtube: Itâ€™s a rich source of tutorials and project demonstrations for Arduino enthusiasts.        Q12: Think of a medical or health-related device that you could build using a microcontroller such as an Arduino. Describe the device, what it is useful for, and how it would work, with a brief discussion of the features you would use to make the device function.        A medical device that I could build using a microcontroller such as an Arduino is the  Finger Pulse Oximeter.  It is used to measure blood oxygen saturation (SpO2) and heart rate. The device uses LEDs to emit light through a finger, which is then measured by a photodetector to determine the SpO2 and calculate   the heart rate. The microcontroller controls the LEDs, reads the photodetector signal, processes the data to calculate SpO2 and heart rate, and displays the results on a screen.            Features:          LEDs: Emit light at specific wavelengths (usually red) to penetrate the skin and blood.          Photodetector: Detect the light transmitted through the finger and convert it into an electrical signal.          Signal Processing: Algorithms to process the photodetector signal and calculate SpO2 and heart rate. User Interface: Buttons or a touchscreen to control the device and navigate menus.          Power Supply: Battery or external power source to power the device.        Note: Alternatively, an oximeter sensor such as the MAX30101 by SparkFun can be used in replacement of the LEDs and the photodetector. The MAX30101 performs sensing by using its internal LEDs to bounce light off the arteries and arterioles in the finger's subcutaneous layer, while its photodetectors sense how much light is absorbed.     *************************************    Sincerely,  Cindy N.

Katerina Ramos, Red Wolf Education & Outreach Coordinator, NCWF <katerina@ncwf.org>  : Fri, May 17, 2024 at 8:30 AM  Subject: Step Up for Red Wolves  To: <tlbelus@ncsu.edu>  â€Š  Good morning Trisha,        Today is Endangered Species Day and you have an opportunity to protect, conserve, and restore Red Wolves in the wild in North Carolina. As one of the most endangered canids in the world, only found in the wild in North Carolina, what could be a greater purpose on this Endangered Species Day?        To get inspired, watch my brief video below to learn about Red Wolves and why Endangered Species Day is so important.    Endangered Species Day message from NCWF Red Wolf Education & Outreach Coordinator  With 17 known Red Wolves in the wild, they are threatened daily by roads and vehicles running throughout their habitat as well as by gunshot. NCWF is committed to addressing these risks.        When you drive on U.S. Highway 64 towards Alligator River National Wildlife Refuge, you will likely see electronic signage telling you to slow down because you're in Red Wolf territory. NCWF helped pay for these signs and is advocating for more fencing and wildlife crossings to prevent Red Wolf and other wildlife vehicle collisions.        You may also see signs on private property that read "Prey for the Pack". NCWF works with U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service and private landowners on the Albemarle Peninsula to expand Red Wolf habitat by making habitat improvements that benefit Red Wolves, other wildlife, and the landowner through this cost-share program.        I work every day to raise awareness about Red Wolves by operating the Red Wolf Center in Columbia, North Carolina. However, my favorite way to share the Red Wolf story is taking people out on the Alligator River and Pocosin Lakes National Wildlife Refuges to experience Red Wolf habitat and all the wildlife that live there.        Come visit me at the Red Wolf Center and in the meantime, I invite you to donate to NCWF's Endangered Species May campaign to raise $10,000 by the end of May for Red Wolves, other listed wildlife, and those of greatest conservation need in North Carolina.        We are lucky here in North Carolina, to be home to the world's only wild Red Wolves. Let's not let them go extinct on our watch!        Thank you for caring and I hope to see you at the Red Wolf Center soon! Tim Gestwicki, CEO, NCWF <tim@ncwf.org>  : Thu, May 16, 2024 at 8:31 AM  Subject: Remembering Extinct Wildlife in NC  To: <tlbelus@ncsu.edu>  Trisha,        I often get questions about the prominent bison in NCWF's logo. It was introduced in 1969 to commemorate the organizationâ€™s 25th anniversary. It symbolizes NCWF's vision and strengths.        The National Bison Legacy Act, passed by Congress in April 2016, made the bison a U.S. symbol of resilience, unity, and healthy landscapes and communities.        Bison, unlike cattle, do not turn their backs to storms and bad weather, but face directly into the rain and winds. Like the bison, NCWF is agile, strong, dedicated to the cause, and faces a challenge full on.        Maybe one day the bison will be reintroduced in the wild in North Carolina too.        Other extinct species that once called North Carolina home, include the Carolina parakeet, passenger pigeon, and Bachman's warbler.        Though these species are some of the few to go fully extinct since colonization, they are not alone in facing threats of extinction, and they are certainly not the only ones to experience significant population declines at the hands of market hunting, habitat loss, and resource scarcity.        Tomorrow is Endangered Species Day and NCWF is raising awareness about endangered, threatened, and species of greatest conservation need in order to prevent further losses. You can make a difference right now by doing two things:        Read more about extinct wildlife in North Carolina  Donate to NCWF's Endangered Species May campaign to raise $10,000 by the end of May to support NCWF's work to protect, conserve, and restore listed species and those of greatest conservation need.      Losing wildlife affects us all. Together, we can make a difference.        Thank you,    Tim    Donate  	  Tim Gestwicki    CEO    North Carolina Wildlife Federation    1346 St. Julien Street    Charlotte, NC 28205    Phone (704) 332-5696     Web www.ncwf.org Email Tim@ncwf.org    P.S. Megan Coursey <meganpc@comcast.net>  to:	Victoria Cetrone <VCetrone@olgchs.org>  :	May 4, 2024, 12:31â€¯PM  Hello Ms. Cetrone,     Please do not tell Hayden I sent you this email. He doesn't like us contacting his teachers and we encourage him to be as independent as possible with contacting teachers himself. However, it is still our responsibility to ensure that his anxiety and ADHD are under the best control possible and that he is utilizing all tools available to cope with both conditions. Therefore, I am contacting you to be sure there isn't something he is missing. Unfortunately, his anxiety holds him back from reaching out to teachers in situations where he knows he messed up something big.       We all understand that the responsibility for this situation lies entirely on Hayden, and nothing in this email is intended to imply that any of it is on you. My goal is to figure out what Hayden did or didn't do to create this situation so I can provide him with as many tools as possible to avoid it in the future.     The problem is that Hayden had no idea there was going to be a History test yesterday (hence his poor grade). I asked how he was expected to know about the test. He said it was posted in the Google Classroom stream but he keeps forgetting to read that because almost all of the information is redundant. Instead he goes directly to his "to do" list in Google Classroom and accesses his assignments there. We had a long talk about the importance of reading the stream each day even if it seems like a waste of time to him since even one piece of critical information (like your test announcement), makes it worth reading daily.     His not reading the stream and going straight to the "to do" list is partly a function of his anxiety. He is very anxious to get his homework started each night and has a major anxiety spike if he has to do anything prior to starting on his work. This  plays a role in him skipping the feed and going straight to the "to do" list. Again - not making excuses for him, I just want you to understand in case you have any helpful ideas. I am hoping that this experience will make him feel the same urgency over missing information in the stream as he has over getting his homework completed. Additionally, we discussed how he could utilize his planner to help remember to check the stream.     So my question to you is whether there was any other way Hayden should have known about the test. Did he miss an announcement in class? Was it posted elsewhere that he should have seen? If the answer is simply that he needs to be better about checking the stream then I think we have done all we can on that for the time being.

Jamie Larsen <jlarsen@ncsu.edu>  to:	 :	Mar 6, 2024, 9:15â€¯AM  subject:	Re: ACTIVITY 3.5: FORMULATING AN ARGUMENT  Hi Chloe, For Assignment 3A, I am not asking you to make up any background experience. Your ethos will simply be based on the correctness and professionalism of the overall formal proposal.    I am sending the following information each of your team members in response to this online activity:    Be sure to read all of the notes about each section that is required for Assignment 3A â€“ Collaborative Instruction Proposal. The notes for the proposal body include information about writing step-by-step instructions. The following â€œmust haveâ€ list should help you get started on writing instructions if you have not already started:    Introduction and informative title â€“ Tell the user in one line, and in more detail what he/she will be accomplishing by using the instructions. Include all materials that are needed, as well as time required.    Step-by-step list â€“ Use numbered lists with each step beginning with a very specific action verb followed by a description of the expected reaction or result, or a common problem that may occur if the action is done incorrectly    Format, fonts, and figures â€“ Use an easy to follow format with varying fonts to give the users cues about what the information provides (e.g., bold for all actions, a different font for cautions, warning, and dangers, etc.). Use visuals with proper labels to illustrate complex steps, or ones that require an important outcome.    Cautions, Warnings, and Danger Notices â€“ Use the legally correct level of warning. A lot of instructions do not meet that standard for what could happen if an action is taken by a user (e.g., Cautions are used if a wrong result can occur; Warnings are used if something can be broken; Dangers are used if physical harm can result.). Also, include appropriate warning notices in the steps where they apply.    Conclusion â€“ Provide information that recaps what the final result should be, as well as information for additional information or support.    Take a moment to look at a quick some notes about Professional and Writing/Instructions, which have some good tips about instruction writing, as well as usability testing - https://en.wikibooks.org/wiki/Professional_and_Technical_Writing/Instructions    Have a great day.    Jamie

to:	Disability Resource Office Testing <dro-testing@ncsu.edu>  :	Dec 11, 2023, 11:06â€¯AM  subject:	 CSC 246 Exam  Good Morning,    I wanted to reach out about my 8AM exam this morning that is to be rescheduled for Wednesday. The 2PM option works for me.      Secondly, I'd like to point out the following:   I understand there is nothing that could really be done, and my exam was likely going to be rescheduled regardless. But I think it was highly inconsiderate how it was handled. I know the office received notice from my professor before 8 AM this morning that my exam was not to be taken today; because when I arrived prior to 8AM, I was informed that my professor did not want me taking it today. As a DISABILITY resource office, I would like to think the office would understand the potential harm to one of their registered students for not informing them ASAP. Even if the office did not know until the first person arrived this morning, an email would have been much better. To give you a sense this is where I stand now:  I am a student with ADHD, I took my meds at 6AM so that they could be in effect by 8AM. This means, they will no longer be working around 6-7 PM this evening. I have an exam today at 3:30, so my priority from getting home this morning to 3:30 will be studying for that exam. When I get home around 4:30 or 5, I will have approximately an hour of study time (as my meds will not be working past 6). I have two exams the next day at 8AM and 2PM, so my focus will be my 8AM exam, leaving me with no prep for my 2PM exam. Then, I get home another day at 5:45, after a day of taking my meds at 6AM and will barely be able to study for my NOW Wednesday exam at 2PM. So now, I have almost 2 days to lose all knowledge for my exam. Of course this is a bit of an exaggeration, and since I have lived with ADHD for almost 21 years, I have mechanisms to try and study after my meds are worn off, but I still am not as productive.     I know there was not much you could do, but I want to bring attention to how highly inconsiderate it was to not inform me immediately after knowing the situation. And how ESPECIALLY inconsiderate it was to send me my location notice at 5:19 PM if you guys had already known (which I suspect/hope you did not). I do appreciate your time and effort to reschedule my exam. I just wanted to let you know so that maybe if this happens to another/with another student in the future it can be prevented.

If you have finished it correctly, just ignore this email.  The comments I keep sharing:    Make it public.  I can't see it until you do.    Upload the link to the actual LiveBinder from your account.  I need to see your LiveBinder project, not just all the documents and assignments from this course.    Take all first person references out of your research.  There are no "I," "me," "my," etc. in professional research.  You use phrases such as "the authors share.....", or "according to (author) in (article) ........, or " research show that...."    Remove all class headings from all assignments.  This should not read like a compilation of class work.  In fact, your name is only on your LiveBinder.    You will not need an outline AND a table of contents.  They are the same, so pick one.    Avoid links inside LiveBinder.  Use as few as possible.  Each new tab should not be another link to open.  Think about your Week 8 presentation and how smoothly you will want to move from one document to the next.    Make sure all pictures and videos are right side up.  Some are posting sideways.    I've only had 2 (out of 20) that I graded.  All others needs at least some tweaking.  So let's just say you edit this weekend and I begin to grade Monday.  Review yours for all the notes above and resubmit when you've had a chance to clean it up.  Message or email me if you have additional questions.    Kaitlyn has agreed to provide assistance if needed.  You can email her at kaiburdette@augusta.edu.
